photo.description: Opened in 1929, this 5,000 seat movie palace has a mix of Islamic and Egyptian architectural elements. It was originally built for the Shriners, before it was rented out to William Fox and opened just days before the start of the Great Depression. It managed to recover as the only theater in Atlanta to allow both Black and White patrons, though the theater itself was segregated. By 1974 however, the theater was declining again and there were plans to tear down the theater. Public outcry and a massive publicity campaign saved the building, and it is now a National Natural Landmark. Atlanta, Georgia
